article.headline: USC 72, Oregon State 70
article.story: CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- With time running down, Southern Cal's Nick Young just wants the ball in his hands. He knew just what to do with it Thursday night, knocking down a 17-footer with 0.8 seconds left to lead the Trojans to a 72-70 overtime win over Oregon State. "Great players take big shots like that, and I've always wanted to take big-time shots," said the 6-foot-6 sophomore swingman. "When the time comes, I don't run from it." Young embraced his chances all game, particularly in the first half, when he scored 19 of his game-high 25 points. Lodrick Stewart added 18 for the Trojans (13-6, 4-4 Pacific-10), who bounced back from a 66-45 loss to UCLA last week. Chris Stephens and Nick DeWitz had 16 points apiece to lead the Beavers (10-9, 3-5). The score was tied at 70 when Stephens made two free throws with 14.9 seconds left. With 7 seconds left, Young got the ball at the top of the key, started to drive, then pulled up on DeWitz and swished the shot while falling away. The Beavers could not get a final shot following a timeout. With the victory, the Trojans surpassed last season's 12 wins. Center Abdoulaye N'diaye added 12 points and eight rebounds. Sasa Cuic had 13 points and Jason Fontenet had 11 off the bench for the Beavers, whose last three losses have come in the final seconds. Oregon State went up 10-0 to start the game but grew cold in a turnover-plagued first half. USC went on a 16-2 run to take the lead and increased the advantage as leading-scorer Young heated up. Young made 7 of 8 first half shots as the Trojans, who shot 56 percent, took a 38-29 lead into halftime. The Beavers regained the lead when Marcel Jones made the first of two free throws and DeWitz tipped in the miss on the second to make it 52-49. Stephens and Cuic hit 3-pointers to put Oregon State ahead 60-59 with 2:05 to play, but Gabe Pruitt, who been quiet on offense throughout the game, countered with a 3-pointer with 1:38 left. N'diaye made one of two free throws to make it 63-60 for the Trojans, but Stephens buried an off-balance 3-pointer to tie the game with 28.7 seconds left. USC played for the final shot, but Pruitt's 3-point attempt at the buzzer missed and the game went to overtime. After beating then-No.24 Arizona two weeks ago, the Beavers have let two straight winnable home games get away. They lost to Arizona State 65-63 in overtime on Jan. 14. DeWitz believes Oregon State has been playing down to its opponent. "Our focus isn't there when we're not playing UCLA, Arizona or Cal," he said. "We play harder when a better team is out there, I guess." Beaver coach Jay John disagreed with DeWitz's assessment, pointing out that the Beavers have been practicing hard, and preparing well for all opponents. "(The Trojans)probably shot as well as they've shot in the Pac-10 all year," he said. Pruitt, averaging 16 points a game, had 10 points and six assists. He also contributed on defense, containing Stephens, Oregon State's leading scorer, for long stretches. Pruitt fouled out in overtime, or he might have been the one to take USC's final shot. Trojan coach Tim Floyd was hoping Young would attack the basket on the final shot. "What we didn't want was a jump shot," he said. "Thankfully, it went in." The Beavers were again without starting point guard Lamar Hurd, who is out with a groin injury. His replacement, Wesley Washington, had three assists and six turnovers. ^
